[Heltec NrfTracker v2] 

First I would like to start by saying that when approched by Heltec Automations to test one of their new products yet to be released I was glad to assist. 
Please note this is a sample product that has yet to release and further revisions may change with the final product. 

[Q&A]: 

What is the Heltec NrfTracker v2? 

A cost effective unlicensed and decentralized radio that operates using LoRa modulation. Capable of bluetooth, lora, gnss (gps), as well as additional hardware or sensors can added using the serial serial gpio pins for developers. 

What differentiates the Heltec NrfTracker v2 from other LoRa Radios? 

First we should look at the specifications of the radio. We have a change from esp32 to nrf52 which improves the power efficiency, improvement to the transmitsion output power from 22+-dBm to 28+-dBm, a built in gps that does not require any external installtion, and solar charging capable. 
These 4 are the primary differences from other similar LoRa or Heltec products.  

How easy is it to remove the screen? 

Simple enough; the screen is held to the board by 4 screws and on the underside of the display connects via a delicate ribbon cable.
Note that the front panel display may need to be temporaily removed in order to safely solder to the gpio pins for additional external hardware. 

What firmware does the NrfTracker v2 comes with?

Shipped with the sample radio it came preinstalled with Meshtastic version 2.7.19. Once released you can update your device to newer versions using. https://flasher.meshtastic.org/
This however is not the only option, you can also install a alternitive firmware called Meshcore version 1.14. Once released you can update your device to a newwer version using. https://flasher.meshcore.co.uk/

Does Heltec provide a LoRawan or other in house firmware? 

Currently only Meshtastic and Meshcore firmwares are offically supported at this time. 

What kind of range will I get using this radio?

That's a difficult question to anwser because it depends on a number of factors like other nodes to Hop off of, radio preset ie LongFast, Elevation, Line of sight, Antenna quality, Antenna tuned freqency, Background noise, Regional restrictions
Realisticly from point A-B with no hops you could be looking at anywhere from 2km to 10km+, but the range can be improves with filter, higher gain antennas, and most importently elevation. 

I see a Ipex port for GNSS (GPS) do I need to install a antenna? 
No. The positional radio GNSS has a built in antenna however if you would like to install a external GNSS antenna you can. Requires you to modify the circuit by adding a 0-ohm resistor (or other conductive metal or cable) to connect to the IPEX interface.

Can this be used primarily as a real time tracker?

Maybe. I would classify this radio as a last resort when all other stable means of communicating are unavalible. Within local range (lets say within 5km) of multiple nrftracker's you could perform real time tracking. How far you can push that in distence from each other depends on Hops, Mqtt from you or neighbours, and Line of Sight, Antenna type, ect. 

What will happen if it doesn't update frequently? 

It will appear as if your node jumps locations as it comes into proximity to another node that might need to relay back to your monitoring radio if a direct connection isn't possible. If too far from other nodes or poor signal you might not be able to see positional updates but they will still be sent.

What in meshtastic should I set the radio to be best configured for tracking? 

Role Tracker https://meshtastic.org/docs/configuration/radio/device/

Posisitonal configuration https://meshtastic.org/docs/configuration/radio/position/ 

Broacast to mesh by default is 15 minutes you may want to decrease that time if your not using smart positioning. For my testing I did not using Smart Positioning to give myself consistent conditions.



[Notes as I inspect the radio] 

Hardware design
-Pro’s: rev 1.0 of the nrftracker v2 Design seems nice close to feeling like it has it's own enclosure just from the front panel. 
-Con’s: Front panel display may need to be removed in order to safely solder to the gpio pins. 

Display
-Pro’s: bright small but easy to read screen. Screen removal appears easy enough by removing 4 small screws, just need to be careful seperating the screen from the board as their is a ribbon cable you need to carefully unplug.  
-Con’s: screen size could be a bit bigger. but it functions. 

Radio type
-Pro’s: sx1262 common second generation radio prefered over the first generation radio like the 127x. 
Tests: RF Meter show's the full TX output to be 28.22 dBm +- and before the internal power amplifier the sx1262 supports 22 dBm verified within the meshtastic debug logs on boot of the node. See: https://github.com/Nullvoid3771/Heltec-Projects.-/issues/1#issuecomment-4247379117
-Con’s: third lr1121 and forth generation radios lr2021 include dual frequency SubGhz eg. 868 915Mhz and 2.4Ghz. Might be the better choice in the future; except it will need the internal Power amplifiers also to reach 28dBm like the prior generations.  

User provided antenna
-Pro’s: Heltec whip antenna so the antenna is known. ipex to sma pigtail. 
Base Antenna: 
-Con’s: No antenna or pigtail was provided, but I had some. 

Enclosure 
-Currently no 3d printed models are avalible yet so a less complex approch was taken and used a modified advil bottle.   

Lora antenna port
-Pro’s: Ipex which is fairly standard and provides flexibility in tigher enclosures. 
-Con’s: Ipex is known to be easier to damage accidentially. a stright sma port maybe bettter, at risk of flexibily in enclosure design. 

Bluetooth antenna port (if applicable)
-Pro’s: Built in. 
-Con’s: no external ipex for bluetooth.

GNSS antenna port 
-Pro’s: Has a built in GNSS antenna, but optionally has the ability to use your own GNSS antenna. 
-Con’s: need to wire a resister to the board to use ipex. 

Microcontroller
-Pro’s: nRF52 more power efficent lacks wifi and a secondary core. 
-Con’s: compared to the esp32 it does lack wifi and a core but gains power efficentcy. 

IO interfaces
-Does the hardware feature enough free GPIO ports for your applications? Y/N Why?: Y Has 2 sets of free gpio pins. I don't really add to much to gpio normally, but I can imagine some people like to add more.  
-Bluetooth (list any issues): No issues found, connects well using the meshtastic web client via bluetooth to PC. 
-GPIO (list any issues if applicable): N/A Haven't explored that far in it's use to try anything with gpio. 
-Serial USB (list any issues if applicable): No issues found using the meshtastic web client and serial to device.

Input buttons
-Pro’s: Has enough buttons to get the job done. Easy to navigate the basicUI menu from meshtastic. Button's have a good click to them; not worried about any flexing from button pressing.  
-Con’s: None really. 

GPS
-Pro’s: Built in UC6580 GNSS, Doesn't require soldering or plugging in a external module. optional gnss ipex port. offers more satellites then the US only GPS. 
-Con’s: N/A

